\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{y=Ax}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mathbf{y}}{\partial\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{A}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}=\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{ik}x_{k}
\]

\end_inset

it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial y_{i}}{\partial x_{j}}=a_{ij}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{y=Ax}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times1$
